WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.360
Hello everyone. I guess many, if not most of you already know that you can create really beautiful

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:16.000
publication-ready data visualizations with ggplot2. But did you know you can create visualizations like this?

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:19.540
Or this?

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:23.059
Or those?

00:00:23.059 --> 00:00:35.060
So I'll be talking about making such creative visualizations with R and ggplot2 and you may ask why?

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:44.020
Well, I believe that creative plots, creative visualizations stand out. It makes it easier for

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:51.299
your viewer, your audience to connect with it, to engage with it. They're more memorable

00:00:52.259 --> 00:00:57.540
and in the end it helps you get your message across easily.

00:01:00.419 --> 00:01:04.660
And for some people it's just a matter of self-expression. Some people just want to be

00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:11.379
creative and my feeling is that when most people talk about being creative, what they actually mean

00:01:11.459 --> 00:01:13.300
is having a personal style.

00:01:16.019 --> 00:01:23.940
There are many definitions of creativity but most of them have three elements in common.

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:29.540
The first one is novelty. Creativity is about coming up with something new.

00:01:31.779 --> 00:01:34.500
It's about coming up with a solution to a problem.

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:40.739
And then it's about taking different concepts, different elements and combining them,

00:01:40.739 --> 00:01:48.339
combining them, making something new out of them. But what I like most is this

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:57.540
this concept, this element that's from the definition of humor. So combining seemingly

00:01:58.339 --> 00:02:05.220
unrelated concepts, it's what can create a sense of surprise, like in this image.

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:15.220
Now, data visualizations are a very broad field. You can be creative by using many different tools,

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:19.460
many different techniques and materials, different materials even.

00:02:19.619 --> 00:02:27.860
But our tool is codes, R and ggplot. So we're going to spend some time about talking

00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:35.460
about ggplot specifically. And R, being a programming language, has the advantage of

00:02:37.619 --> 00:02:44.740
letting you create almost anything you want. And more specifically, ggplot2 has this flexibility

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:50.660
and it's customizable. As Thomas mentioned, it's built on the grammar of graphics.

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:55.139
And on top of that, there are many other packages

00:02:56.899 --> 00:03:00.820
called extensions that are built onto ggplot and expand its capabilities.

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:10.020
So we'll talk about the three parts of the process, how you can find creative ideas about your plots,

00:03:10.179 --> 00:03:16.020
creative ideas about your plots, how you can get more creative when you're actually coding,

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:20.660
and then how you can make it a bit more personal, have a personal style.

00:03:23.139 --> 00:03:30.259
So how do you find ideas? Well, the most obvious thing to do is to look what other people do,

00:03:30.259 --> 00:03:38.179
get inspired by others. And when you see something you like, a visualization you like,

00:03:38.740 --> 00:03:45.940
spend a couple of minutes and try to break down the plots. I mean, what's the thing you like most?

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:55.300
It's the visualization itself. Is it colors? Is it something else? And by doing this, you can

00:03:55.300 --> 00:04:03.940
train your eye and find maybe some ideas for your next plots and use those ideas.

00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:13.220
For example, here is a chart I saw on the left side, and I really like this 3D effect,

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:15.220
so I recreated it with ggplot.

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:26.500
Another way is to try out new packages. There are many packages out there, and this can also be

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:34.980
This can also be an inspiration, see different charts. I've been having a lot of fun with

00:04:35.859 --> 00:04:38.019
ggcirclepack the last few weeks.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:46.980
And if you are more used to a certain kind of visualizations or plots,

00:04:48.179 --> 00:04:53.220
you may want to see what people in other fields do, what their charts look like.

00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:03.059
Like here, for example, on the left-hand side, that was an early Japanese chart,

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:13.380
the anchor chart that is used for mapping stock prices on a line, and I use it from

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:19.299
a chart about the Great British Bake Off. I mean, why not?

00:05:19.779 --> 00:05:20.260
Why not?

00:05:23.059 --> 00:05:30.820
Another way to maybe come up with ideas is to slow down the process, so instead of jumping

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:40.820
right into coding, sit down, take a piece of paper or your tablet and draw up, sketch out some ideas.

00:05:41.059 --> 00:05:47.779
Data visualizations. Visualization has a lot of rules, guidelines, what you should do,

00:05:47.779 --> 00:05:53.540
what you shouldn't do, and most of the time you should follow those rules, but

00:05:55.299 --> 00:06:02.100
you can try to break them instead. One of the rules is that you shouldn't plot, I don't know,

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:10.420
hundreds of lines, because as a line chart, this plot is totally useless, but when you combine

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:17.619
all the lines together, you can see different patterns. So in that way, it may work.

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:27.619
You may want to look at data art or even try to do some data art. It's a totally different field.

00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:31.380
You can visualize data in different ways.

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:41.140
And if you're really, really desperate, you can always ask chatGPT or another large language

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:50.019
model. Maybe it's not that useful all the times, but here you see number four, 3D data sculptures.

00:06:50.019 --> 00:06:51.619
I wouldn't have thought that.

00:06:51.779 --> 00:07:02.019
So, let's have a look at some tips on how you can be creative when coding. And again,

00:07:02.739 --> 00:07:08.820
the obvious thing is look what other people do. It's very common within the art community to

00:07:08.820 --> 00:07:14.660
share your code when you share a visualization online. So if you have a lot of data,

00:07:15.619 --> 00:07:23.619
there's a link to the GitHub repo. Go there and see what kind of code they used to do it in.

00:07:29.619 --> 00:07:34.339
That's similar to the first tip about finding ideas,

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:42.980
or remixing. It's more of an exercise. I really like to recreate charts I'd see and they're made

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:51.299
with whatever tool, try to recreate them with ggplot. And the goal here is to make it as close

00:07:51.299 --> 00:07:58.899
to the original as possible. And it's good to have a lot of data, but it's also good to have a lot of

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:02.339
The goal here is to make it as close to the original as possible.

00:08:03.619 --> 00:08:10.260
And it's good because it puts some constraints. You have a goal and you have problems. You have

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:16.579
to come up with solutions. And that's a great way to learn how to do things with ggplot.

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:25.940
Here, for example, is the Eurovision Song Contest scoreboard. And I recreated it in ggplot2 and

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:28.260
it's pretty much the same.

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:39.460
You can try different options, different parameters in your ggplot functions.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:44.340
Try to break things, use extreme values in your functions.

00:08:46.659 --> 00:08:54.340
I don't know, draw very thick lines, very thin lines, huge text, see how it works.

00:08:56.659 --> 00:08:59.380
And it's about getting to know your tool.

00:09:04.500 --> 00:09:10.900
Another way to be more creative is to use the different geons beyond their intended

00:09:12.659 --> 00:09:20.020
use and purpose. I try to think the different geons as building tools or drawing tools.

00:09:20.979 --> 00:09:28.580
For me, geon point is not about making scatter plots. It's about drawing plots,

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:37.619
drawing points. And the same goes for geon line. It's not about making line charts. It's about

00:09:37.619 --> 00:09:44.500
drawing lines. That helps you free your mind from the constraints. Now, I don't know what the

00:09:44.739 --> 00:09:51.059
intended use for geon-beast line is. I should ask Thomas about it. But I'm sure it's not about

00:09:51.059 --> 00:10:05.299
drawing penguins. I really like text and visualizations made with text. And I think

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:13.859
text in general is underused because there's potential.

00:10:15.539 --> 00:10:21.219
You can map your variables to different fonts, different colors, different sizes.

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:29.940
And if there's something you want to do and there isn't a geon function

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:36.500
about it, you can create your own. That's the beauty of using R.

00:10:37.539 --> 00:10:43.299
And I've tried a couple of times. I haven't really succeeded. But you may have better luck.

00:10:49.299 --> 00:10:57.539
That's a very useful function that I've been using the past year or so. And what it does is

00:10:58.099 --> 00:11:07.059
if you give it a ggplot object, it returns a data frame with all the points or shapes

00:11:07.780 --> 00:11:14.979
with their coordinates and their properties, which then you can use to make another plot.

00:11:16.179 --> 00:11:26.260
So, here on the left, my first plot was a beeswarm plot. And I passed it to ggplot build.

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:34.500
And then used this data frame to draw images, these little small album covers,

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:46.820
and put labels and everything. I really like participating in online challenges.

00:11:47.700 --> 00:11:54.979
I've been doing Tidy Tuesday for years. It's a weekly challenge where you get a data frame

00:11:55.539 --> 00:12:00.419
and you create a plot, which then you share online.

00:12:01.619 --> 00:12:06.099
It's been the best way for me to learn and experiment, try out new things.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:14.020
The great thing about challenges is that it's a low-risk environment. I mean, it's not your work.

00:12:14.979 --> 00:12:19.380
You don't feel any pressure to do something specific. You can do whatever you want.

00:12:20.179 --> 00:12:25.219
And you can also get feedback from the community, which most of the time is positive.

00:12:26.099 --> 00:12:33.539
We all know that our people are really nice. So, you never get really negative feedback.

00:12:34.260 --> 00:12:37.940
People are nice to you. They offer suggestions to make things better.

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:47.859
The last part is about having a personal style. And it's probably the hardest part.

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:53.700
It's difficult to give advice without sounding like, you know, be yourself.

00:12:55.619 --> 00:12:59.219
I don't know. Which, by the way, is not the best advice, always.

00:13:00.659 --> 00:13:03.380
But hopefully, there are a few things you can do.

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:10.179
For me, I think the most important is not using the defaults.

00:13:10.739 --> 00:13:17.619
You can go a really long way just by not using the default fonts or the default colors in ggplot.

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:25.140
There are hundreds of fonts out there, if not thousands, hundreds of color palettes,

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:32.020
layers, and so on. So, I think it's important to have a personal style.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:40.099
And find what works for you. Don't forget about accessibility.

00:13:44.260 --> 00:13:50.820
Sometimes, when we want to be creative, we tend to overdo it, to overcomplicate things.

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:54.979
So, it's good to remember that there is another way to do it.

00:13:54.979 --> 00:14:01.059
So, we can try and remove things to make it simpler. And that can be very creative.

00:14:04.179 --> 00:14:09.140
And in order to find your personal style, you have to actually do it.

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:14.179
So, you have to try new things, see what works, what doesn't work.

00:14:15.059 --> 00:14:19.619
And it sometimes can be a little scary, or you feel insecure.

00:14:21.219 --> 00:14:26.659
Should I do this more creative plot? Maybe it's a little risky.

00:14:26.979 --> 00:14:35.219
My advice here is to maybe create two versions. One more conventional, one more creative.

00:14:35.219 --> 00:14:42.739
So, I mean, if there's something you want to share with others, it's better to have both.

00:14:42.739 --> 00:14:49.380
So, you don't feel like you are too much out of your comfort zone.

00:14:50.340 --> 00:14:58.419
If you're doing creative visualizations in your free time, you may want to try and do

00:14:58.419 --> 00:15:08.419
a plot about something you like. Maybe a TV show, gardening, basketball, I don't know, whatever.

00:15:08.419 --> 00:15:15.299
It's easier to engage, be creative with subjects.

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:21.140
Engage, be creative with subjects that you actually like.

00:15:26.099 --> 00:15:33.140
And another advice I would like to give to all of you is to keep all the ideas

00:15:34.260 --> 00:15:38.580
or things you come up with. It can be a notebook, save your bookmarks,

00:15:40.419 --> 00:15:44.260
make it easy for you, because inspiration doesn't come when you want it.

00:15:45.780 --> 00:15:52.820
So, it's good to have material. So, when you're going to make a plot, you can go back and say,

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:54.979
yeah, I like this one, I will try it.

00:15:57.140 --> 00:16:02.419
If you get inspired by someone or use their codes, please be nice, give them credit.

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:14.580
And especially if you share it online, it's good to acknowledge other people's work.

00:16:14.659 --> 00:16:21.539
And if you're not sharing, I like to, for example, I like to put a comment in my code,

00:16:22.659 --> 00:16:26.099
in case someone sees it. It would be nice to see their name.

00:16:28.099 --> 00:16:37.780
And to contradict myself a bit here, I certainly believe that you should try and be more creative,

00:16:37.780 --> 00:16:47.140
but creativity shouldn't be a goal in itself. And if you do try and be creative and it does

00:16:47.140 --> 00:16:53.940
really work, don't get discouraged, because, yeah, you can be creative all the time.

00:16:53.940 --> 00:17:01.140
I'm certainly not. Most of my plots are really simple, not creative at all, and sometimes are

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:09.219
like disasters, like this one. But the thing is, it's okay. I mean, that's the point. You have to

00:17:09.219 --> 00:17:19.380
train. And I want to leave you with these words that make it a habit, practice regularly, try out

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:25.699
things as often as you can, make lots of plots, share it with people, get feedback, what works

00:17:25.699 --> 00:17:35.300
for you, what works for others. You can find the slides and links to different resources

00:17:36.420 --> 00:17:39.300
on this link. Thank you so much.

